SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION 17 CFR Part 229 Release No. 33-11276 (Amendment)

Section 229.106 - Cybersecurity Incident Disclosure (Amended)

(a) Material Incident Disclosure. Registrants shall disclose any cybersecurity incident that the registrant determines to be material within forty-eight (48) hours of such materiality determination. The disclosure shall be made on Form 8-K Item 1.05 and shall include:
(1) The nature, scope, and timing of the incident;
(2) The material impact or reasonably likely material impact on the registrant and its operations;
(3) Whether the incident has been contained or is ongoing;
(4) Any remediation measures taken or planned.

(b) Incident Response Documentation. Registrants shall maintain documented incident response procedures that include:
(1) Defined severity classification criteria for cybersecurity incidents;
(2) Escalation timelines from detection to executive notification (maximum 4 hours for critical incidents);
(3) Board-level reporting procedures for material incidents within 24 hours of classification;
(4) Post-incident review requirements within 30 days of incident containment;
(5) Evidence preservation protocols ensuring forensic data is retained for a minimum of five (5) years.

(c) Annual Cybersecurity Governance Report. Registrants shall file an annual report (Form 10-K Item 106) describing:
(1) The board of directors' oversight of cybersecurity risks and the committee structure responsible;
(2) Management's role in assessing and managing material cybersecurity risks;
(3) The registrant's processes for assessing, identifying, and managing cybersecurity threats;
(4) Whether and how the registrant uses third-party assessors, auditors, or consultants for cybersecurity;
(5) The frequency of cybersecurity training provided to personnel and the percentage of personnel trained.

(d) Third-Party Risk Management. Registrants shall maintain an inventory of all third-party service providers with access to material information systems, and shall conduct annual security assessments of such providers. Contracts with material third-party providers shall include:
(1) Mandatory breach notification within 24 hours of incident detection;
(2) Right to audit security controls with 30 days' notice;
(3) Minimum security standards compliance (SOC 2 Type II or equivalent).

(e) Penalties. Failure to comply with this section shall subject the registrant to civil penalties of up to $1,000,000 per violation, and officers may be subject to personal liability under Section 21(d) of the Securities Exchange Act.
